        "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out!         "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out!         "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.)     {
        "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out! Also, last note, if you need to move a deal here in DFW or Houston, we may be able to help! We're primarily a dispo company and yes we have investor lift (again lol) but we're also flipping properties here in DFW. Would love to connect with y'all!",

        "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out! Also, last note, if you need to move a deal here in DFW or Houston, we may be able to help!         "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out!         "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals. Shift your focus to doing cash. You'll do more deals, make more money, and build a business that will thrive.\nIf you have any questions don't hesitate to reach out!         "text": "Probably going to get a lot of heat for this but oh well.\nI've had countless conversations with others in several communities who have been trying to get their first deal done and they're following the guidance from their \"leaders\" but have yet to close a single deal.\nSome of the individuals have been at it for 6-12 months and a few have been at it for even longer! Nuts, right?\nWhat is the common issue with these conversations? They're all focused on wholesaling creative deals.\nNow, I love creative if you're the buyer. It can be a powerful tool for sure! But I despise creative deals if the end goal is just to wholesale them, here is why.\n1.) Cash offers are easier to understand, evaluate, and structure than creative.\n2.) Cash offers are simple to do and creative deals are much more complex.\n3.) You'll make much more money doing a cash deal than a creative by far.\n4.) Your average assignment for a creative deal falls around $5-$10k, I'm averaging around $37k for my assignment fees that are cash offers.\n5.) It's harder to dispo a creative deal because the pool of creative buyers is significantly smaller than the pool of cash buyers.\n6.) Most creative buyers want a low entry fee, which makes it harder to get a good deal.\n7.) You will typically spend more time putting a creative deal together than a cash deal.\n8.) Your entry fee consists of several factors and the more they accumulate the smaller your assignment gets.\n9.) Creative deals bring with them more risks, last thing you want to do is put either party in a sticky situation.\n10.) It's 10x harder to consistently hit 6 figure months when you focus on creative deals, not cash. And if you're leading a team, your team isn't going to eat...\nSo, here is what I recommend doing - Let's call it the \"Darion Method\" Everyone seems to have methods these days lol Jk.\nBut seriously, if any of the points resonate with you, stop focusing on wholesaling creative deals.
